# Writing style (all replies and file edits)

## Bold asterisks (`**`): bullet headings only

- The only allowed use of `**` is a short heading at the start of a list bullet—the label before a colon or em dash, for example: `- Label: body text` where Label is wrapped in `**`. Use this sparingly so scans stay readable.
- Do not use `**` in running prose, paragraphs, table cells, or mid-sentence emphasis. Do not bold random words inside a bullet body.
- Prefer plain words, short sentences, or `` `identifiers` `` / `code` fences when something must stand out outside that bullet-heading pattern.
- If a template or existing file uses `**` elsewhere, only keep it when changing the file would break a required format; otherwise normalize when you touch the file.

## Readable, action-oriented language

- Write in full sentences where they fit—not stacks of labels, telegraphic fragments, or “title case laundry lists” unless the user asked for a strict outline.
- Prefer verbs and outcomes: what to do, what changes, what the reader gets.
- Default tone: direct, human, scannable—like good technical documentation, not a slide deck of slogans.

## Structure

- Prefer shorter paragraphs: about two to three sentences each on average. Break long blocks so the eye can rest; only keep a longer paragraph when it is one tight argument or the user asked for a single block.
- Use concise bullets for steps, options, or lists; each bullet should be a phrase or sentence that can stand alone.
- Avoid Markdown tables unless you truly need many aligned columns (for example four or more columns, or a dense side-by-side comparison). For two or three facts, use short paragraphs or a short bullet list instead.
- When a table is justified, keep headers and cells short and plain—no `**` in cells (the bullet-heading exception applies to list lines, not grid layouts).

## Scope

- Applies to chat answers, comments, `AGENT.md`, `SKILL.md`, READMEs, and any other prose you author or rewrite unless the user explicitly overrides for a one-off.
